@node USAGE "Usage"

@{b}@{u}Usage@{uu}@{ub}

This program is very easy to use, even though it has many options. You must run this from the
shell, here is a template.

@{b}rx RGB2Hex RED/N GREEN/N BLUE/N@{ub}

You must give three numbers repesenting the colour you wish to convert, red, green and blue
respectively and in that order, the /N just means that it is a number. If you enter nothing or
a question mark (?) the usage options will be displayed.

@{b}rx RGB2Hex 50 50 50@{ub}

This is a dark grey, which will be converted to Hexadecimal numbers.

==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==-==

You will then be presented with a prompt for the type of HTML tag you intend to use this
colour in. There are many available options, so here is a list of them all, and the output that they
give. The colour is white, it is just there for the example, your colour will be used when you
run the program.

@{b}Option@{ub}   @{b}Output@{ub}

BODYBG           <BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
BODYALINK        <BODY ALINK="#FFFFFF">
BODYLINK         <BODY LINK="#FFFFFF">
BODYVLINK        <BODY VLINK="#FFFFFF">
BODYTEXT         <BODY TEXT="#FFFFFF">

ALINK            ALINK="#FFFFFF"
LINK             LINK="#FFFFFF"
VLINK            VLINK="#FFFFFF"
TEXT             TEXT="#FFFFFF"

TABLE            <TABLE BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
TR               <TR BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
TH               <TH BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
TD               <TD BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">

FONT             <FONT COLOR="#FFFFFF">

HR               <HR COLOR="#FFFFFF">

When you get the result, you can copy and paste it into your HTML file using @{FG shine}Right-Amiga C@{FG text} to
copy and @{FG shine}Right-Amiga V@{FG text} to paste.

@endnode
@node INSTALL "Installation"

@{b}Installation@{ub}

Installation is very simple, just copy the script to sys:arexx/

You may place this guide wherever you like.

@endnode
@node REQ "Requirements"

@{b}Requirements@{ub}

* An Amiga
* Rexxmast running
* The math function libraries, part of the WB.

This has only been tested on WB 3/3.1, it should also work with WB 2+, but it has not been tested.

@endnode
@node INTRO "Introdution"

@{b}@{u}Introduction@{uu}@{ub}

I wrote this program mainly for myself, but uploaded it as I felt others may also find it useful.
The basic idea is that you enter an RGB colour value in number form and at the end you get a
HTML tag of your choice outputted to you, with the colour you want specified in Hexadecimal form.

You simply give the the red, green and blue number as arguments, and the script does the rest.
You can find these numbers out by using a paint program or similar to find out the values of
the colour you want to create.

You should note that when you are creating web pages you should use hexadecimal numbers to define
colours rather than colour names, as they are more accurate and should give the exact result. This
may depend on how many colours are being used on the screen.

Hope you like it!

@endnode
